      "text": "C. cell–matrix interactions\n\nBased on single-nuclei RNA sequencing studies of skeletal muscle, myotendinous junction (MTJ) myonuclei are specifically enriched for genes involved in cell–matrix interactions. This reflects the specialized function of the MTJ, which is the interface where muscle fibers connect to tendon tissue. The MTJ requires robust structural and adhesive functions to withstand the mechanical forces transmitted between muscle and tendon, making cell–matrix interaction genes (including those encoding extracellular matrix proteins, integrins, and adhesion molecules) particularly important at this specialized compartment. This is distinct from other myonuclear domains such as neuromuscular junction myonuclei (enriched for synaptic transmission genes) or subsynaptic myonuclei."
